            <li class="h2">B</li>
            <div class="li">
                <li>Branch</li>
                <p>When we start a new piece of work or add a new feature to an existing project or deal with an issue we create a new branch. These are used to identify a specific point at which the work was started and once the work has been completed we can merge the branches into the master branch.</p>
            </div>
            <li class="h2">C</li>
            <div class="li">
                <li>Commit</li>
                <p>When something is changed with the code or the project we commit the change, this acts as a "save point" which we can revert back to if needed, or the commit can be used to identify when and where an error has occured. Commits are typically created often and with specific messaged to help devs remember what each commit added or removed from the project.</p>
                <li>Clone</li>
                <p>Clone is a git command line utility that is used to create a clone (copy) of a specific existing repository. This is achieved by running the command <em>"git clone"</em> followed by the HTTP or SSH link on the repo's page.</p>
            </div>
