            <li class="h2">R</li>
            <div class="li">
                <li>Repository</li>
                <p>A git repository is used to track all changes made to files within the project, which will over time build a history of the project. The repository creates a .git folder in the projects folder to allow it to store the changes. If this folder is deleted then so is the project's history.</p>
                <li>Remote</li>
                <p>Remotes in git are used to store the URL of cloned repo's, this is then used by origin when pushing the changes to the repo.</p>
                <li>Rebase</li>
                <p>Rebasing is used to combine the work of two branches together. Rebasing takes a set of commits, then copies these commits and places them somewhere else.</p>
                <li>Reset</li>
                <p>Reset in git is used to revert the changed by moving a branch backwards to an older commit. This will cause the local repository to act as if the latest commit never happened.</p>
                <li>Revert</li>
                <p>Revert in git is used to reverse changes on a remote branch, as reset only works on local branches not remote branches. Revert creates a new commit as there has been changes made to the repository, these changes being reverting the previous commit. Reverting allows for the changes to be pushed for others the view.</p>
